For this assignment, I built a Boggle solver that finds all valid words on a board using a dictionary, employing DFS with backtracking to explore all eight directions while tracking used tiles to prevent letter reuse within a word, and using a prefix set to prune paths that cannot form valid words. The solver returns all words of three or more letters, sorted alphabetically, and ignores case. My initial focus was on correctness and clarity, handling edge cases like empty grids and “Qu” tiles, after which I conducted a peer review with my partner. Their feedback was largely positive, noting solid implementation of DFS and prefix pruning, but they recommended cleaning up comments and typos, standardizing indentation, reducing repeated dictionary and prefix setup code by moving it into a helper function, and clarifying how “Qu” tiles are handled; they confirmed that the three‑letter minimum was correctly enforced. In turn, I reviewed my partner’s solver and highlighted their efficient use of sets and prefix pruning, noted that most edge cases were handled though a few unusual inputs might still cause issues, and suggested clearer variable names, less duplication, and consistent special‑tile handling. Based on the feedback I received, I improved my solver by creating a _build_sets() helper function to centralize dictionary and prefix setup, standardized indentation and comments, split long lines, created a DIRECTIONS list for the eight moves, improved variable names and added explanatory comments, and added validation for empty or invalid grids. Before these changes, linting reported imports not at the top, lines longer than 79 characters, and mixed spaces and tabs; after refactoring, all imports are at the top, long lines are split, and indentation is consistent with four spaces, leaving no linting errors. Regression testing confirmed that my changes did not break functionality: getSolution() still finds all words on the original 4×4 board, empty grids and “Qu” boards work correctly, outputs before and after refactoring are identical, and the three‑letter minimum remains enforced. This code review taught me that readability is crucial even when code works, refactoring pays off by easing future changes, edge cases like multi‑letter tiles and empty boards must be considered, and static analysis catches issues I might otherwise miss. Overall, I now feel more confident reading others’ code, giving constructive feedback, and improving my own code in a professional manner.


